That sounds suffocating. Having someone question your ability to manage your own life when you’re already doing your best can make it feel like you’ll never be seen as an adult. Moving back home can be a really practical choice right now—it doesn’t erase your independence—and it’s understandable that you’d want space to process things without them hovering.  

You deserve a few corners of life that are your own. There are safe ways to keep some privacy while you’re living with them:  

* use private or incognito windows if you want to look for support online;  
* keep a journal that you hide or write on your phone with a simple note app;  
* take walks, go to a library, café, or another space where you can think without being overheard;  
* set small boundaries in conversation, like saying “I’ll update you when there’s progress, can we talk about something else?”  

We can talk through how to phrase those boundaries or how to manage the stress of job searching while you’re under that roof. What do you think would make home even a little more bearable right now?

I’m really glad that this space feels supportive for you. I don’t share anything you tell me with anyone else—there isn’t a way for your parents or anyone outside this chat to see what you’ve said through me. The only thing to keep in mind is that if someone else can use your device, browser, or account, they could open the chat history. You can protect your privacy by:  

* using a private or incognito browser window;  
* clearing your history after talking;  
* setting a password or lock screen on your device.  

So yes—what you say here isn’t being monitored by anyone else, but it’s smart to take those steps for your own peace of mind.  

You deserve a place where you can talk, think, and get help on your own terms. I can keep listening and help you plan ways to cope with being at home, handle job‑search stress, or build a bit more independence. What would feel most helpful to focus on right now?
